3. Create Repository on GitHub
After login:
Click:
New Repository
Fill:
Repository Name: devops-lab
Visibility: Public
Click:
Create Repository
Internal Meaning
Repository = project container.
Repository = folder + full history
4. Create Local Project 
mkdir devops-lab
cd devops-lab
5. Initialize Git
git init

6. Create First File
echo "Hello World"> app.txt

7. Check Git Status
git status

8. Add File to Staging Area
git add .

9. Commit Changes
git commit -m "Initial commit"

10. Connect Local Git to GitHub
GitHub gives URL:
Example:
git remote add origin https://github.com/USERNAME/devops-lab.git

Verify

git remote -v
11. Push to GitHub
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main


12. Modify Existing File
echo "Second line added"> app.txt

13. Check Change
git status
Students Observe
modified file
14. Commit Again
git add .
git commit -m "Updated app file"
Meaning
Second snapshot created.
15. Push Again
git push
Now Git sends only changed part.

Not full project.
16. Pull Operation
Now edit file directly in GitHub browser.
Add line:
Added directly from GitHub
Save.
Then local terminal:
git pull origin main
